Q1. Closure Property of Exponential Distribution (10 points)

A system consists of 20 serially connected, independent parts. Each part has a lifetime described by the exponential distribution, with a mean time to fail of 1500 hours. What is the probability of the system failing within the first 100 hours of use?





Q2. Plan of Experiment (20 points)

We want to verify an estimate of 500 FITs (Failures in Time). We have 2500 parts to test, and we are willing to allow up to 2 parts to fail. (Note: the Failures in Time (FIT) rate of a device means the number of failures expected in \(10^{9}\) device-hours of use.)

  1. How long should the test run, given a 90% level of confidence? (4 points)

  2. If we shrink the confidence level to 60%, how long should the test run? (4 points)

  3. What is the minimum test time with no failure allowed and with 60% confidence? (4 points)

  4. What is the minimum test time with no failure allowed and with 75% confidence? (4 points)

  5. Compare your answers from Question 2a-d. In 2-3 sentences, please explain what they tell us about how we should plan this experiment? (4 points)



Q3. Plan of Experiment (15 points)

You developed a sampling plan designed to screen product lots (meaning: a bunch of items on a production line together). It requires a burn-in period of 300 pieces for 168 hours, with no more than 1 failure allowed for the lot to be accepted with a 60% confidence interval.

  1. How many hours of burn-in are needed to get the same level of failure rate protection if we switched to only accepting lots with ZERO failure? (10 points)

  2. How many units must we ‘burn-in’ if we shorten the time to 48 hours, but keep a 60% confidence level, zero failure allowed, and the same failure rate protection? (5 points)



Q4. Simulating Exponential Failure Times (20 points)

  1. Simulate the failure times of 100 units randomly selected from an exponential population with a mean time to failure of 10,000 hours. Calculate the sample estimate of \(\lambda\) and the Mean Time to Failure (MTTF). (4 points)

  2. Censor your simulated failure times at 2000 hours. Calculate the sample estimate of \(\lambda\) and MTTF, each with a 95% two-sided confidence interval. (4 points)

Note: You no longer have a complete sample, so the mean() will not appropriately capture the mean time to fail. However, you can use the same formula used to estimate lambda from a time-censored crosstabulation.

  1. Repeat parts a and b, but simulate 10,000 units! (8 points)

  2. Compare your results from parts a, b, and c. What happened to your estimates when you increase your sample size? Which sample size is better to use when planning your experiment? (4 points)



Q5. Weibull Distribution (20 points)

A radio manufacturer uses 4 different resistors for a tuner system. The resister manufacturer reports that each resistor has a lifetime modeled adequately by a Weibull distribution, with a shape parameter of 2. These 4 resisters last for 100, 1200, 1500, 2000 hours of radio play time.

  1. What is the life distribution for the time to first resistor failure? Visualize the system life distribution in ggplot over 300 hours. (4 points)

  2. What is the radio’s mean time to failure? (4 points)

  3. What is the median failure time of the radio, given that the failure of any resistor will cause the radio to fail? (4 points)


  1. How likely is it that no resistor fails in the first 168 hours? (4 points)

  2. How likely is it that no resistor fails in the first 1000 hours? (4 points)



Q6. Estimate Failure Rate (35 points)

A complete sample of 100 parts were randomly selected from an assembly line for a life test. The recorded times to failure, in hours, have been listed in the following table. We have reason to believe that this sample comes from a population whose lifetime can be adequately modeled by an exponential distribution.

# You recorded your data like so,
  # with the hours to failure for 100 parts
parts <- tibble(
  hours = c(8, 12, 27, 37, 39, 48, 53, 61, 63, 65, 74, 75, 77, 
            102, 127, 135, 144, 150, 152, 157, 168, 169, 179, 194, 
            201, 227, 229, 239, 247, 247, 248, 260, 263, 265, 
            278, 282, 287, 288, 294, 295, 301, 308, 318, 329, 336, 
            346, 348, 353, 363, 367, 377, 377, 397, 398, 401, 407, 
            417, 417, 422, 435, 447, 457, 469, 471, 488, 495, 496, 
            497, 536, 543, 560, 566, 591, 595, 637, 650, 658, 674, 
            685, 731, 764, 767, 776, 783, 790, 796, 839, 855, 856, 
            856, 865, 869, 896, 918, 962, 970, 1071, 1198, 1219, 1432))

Please analyze this sample using the following steps:

  1. Your company would like to present the data in a simpler format for laypersons. Construct a cross-tabulation, using cell intervals of 100 hours each, ranging from 0 to 1500 hours. (5 points)

  2. Assume an exponential life distribution. Estimate failure rate \(\lambda\) and the mean time to failure, using the formula that best matches the type of data in your sample. (5 points)

  3. Estimate the median time to failure, using your estimate of \(\lambda\) from part b. (5 points)

  4. Assume an exponential life distribution. Calculate (1) 80% and (2) 95% confidence intervals for \(\hat{\lambda}\). (5 points)

  5. Does an exponential function adequately fit your crosstabulated data? Test the model’s goodness of fit using a chi-squared test, evaluating its statistical significance. What is your conclusion? (5 points)

  6. What if the test had stopped after the 40th failure, ending at \(t = 300 \ hours\)? Does the exponential distribution sufficiently describe your new cross-tabulated data now? Estimate \(\hat{\lambda}\), the mean time to failure, and a 60%, two-sided confidence interval for \(\hat{\lambda}\), using the appropriate formula. (5 points)

  7. Can a Weibull distribution model this data better? Repeat your chi-squared test on your data that was censored after the 40th failure, and compare the chi-squared statistic given a shape parameter of 0.5, 0.7, 0.9, 1.1, 1.3, and 1.5. Which of these distributions best fits the data? (5 points)

  • Note: It may help you to write a chisq_test() function.

  • Note: Show and explain each step of your code!

Q8. Simulate Weibull Distribution (20 points)

  1. Simulate a stress test of 100 units, by gathering a random failure time for each of 100 units. Assume that the failure times follow a Weibull distribution, where c = 10,000 hours and m = 0.75. (2 points)

  2. Repeat the simulation 100 times in R. Keep track of all 100 repetitions of the 100 failure times in 1 data.frame. (4 points)

  • Hint: make a data.frame with a vector of 100 repetition id numbers. Then use group_by() and summarize() to make 100 for each repetition id.

  1. For each replicate, rank the failure times, and estimate the characteristic life c using the time to the 63rd failure. Finish by ungroup()-ing the data and sort by replicate. Also, please explain why we use the 63rd failure here! (4 points)

  2. Estimate the mean time to failure, median, and standard deviation of each replicate! Note: please do this using our R workshop functions; please do NOT do this manually (eg. one replicate at a time). (2 points)

  3. Using the estimated characteristic life and median from parts b and c, please estimate the shape parameter for each replication using \(m = \frac{ ln(ln \ 2) }{ ln(T_{50} / c)}\). (4 points)

  • Note: You can use bind_cols() and select() to bind the two data.frames together, among other methods. (Be sure they are both sorted appropriately.)`
  1. Visualize your 100 estimates of c and m, each in a histogram. Describe the results. Are they normally distributed? Where are the means of the 100 estimates for c and m, compared to the true values of c = 10,000 and m = 0.75? (4 points)



Q9. Lognormal Distributions (20 points)

The CDF of the lognormal distribution is written as follows:

\[ F(t) = \Phi ( \frac{ln(t / T_{50} ) }{ \sigma} ) \]

Thanks to the CDF, we know that any variable among \(F(t), t, T_{50}, \sigma\) can be solved for when the values of all the other 3 are known. Given that the population distribution is normal…

  1. Find the median life \(T_{50}\) necessary if 10% of failures occur within 168 hours, with a shape parameter of \(\sigma = 2\). (4 points)

  2. Find the cumulative probability of failure at 1,000 hours, with a median life \(T_{50}\) of 1,000,000 hours and a shape parameter of \(\sigma = 10\). (4 points)

  3. Find the time to achieve 20% failures, with \(T_{50}\) of 50,000 hours and a shape parameter of \(\sigma=1\). (4 points)

  4. Find the shape parameter given for 5% failures in the first 2,000 hours, with a \(T_{50}\) of 50,000 hours. (4 points)

  5. Find the \(T_{50}\) given an average failure rate of 25 FITs over the first 40,000 hours (t = 0 to t = 40,000), with a shape parameter of \(\sigma = 2\). (4 points)

Note: \(FITs = per \ billion \ hours = per \ 10^{9}\).
